<p id="p0102">Similarly, one can linearise constraints of type 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M140" altimg="si117.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mo>(</mo>
    <mi>x</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mo>
    <mn>0</mn>
    <mo>)</mo>
    <mo>∨</mo>
    <mo>(</mo>
    <mi>y</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mo>
    <mn>0</mn>
    <mo>)</mo>
    <mo>,</mo>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> where both 
 <italic>x</italic> and 
 <italic>y</italic> are integer an non-negative. Consider two binary variables 
 <italic>s
  <sub>x</sub>, s
  <sub>y</sub>
 </italic> which will take value 1 if, respectively, 
 <italic>x</italic> and 
 <italic>y</italic> are strictly positive. Then the following three inequalities linearise the original constraint: 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M141" altimg="si118.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>x</mi>
    <mo>≤</mo>
    <mi>M</mi>
    <msub>
     <mi>s</mi>
     <mi>x</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mspace width="0.16em"/>
    <mi>y</mi>
    <mo>≤</mo>
    <mi>M</mi>
    <msub>
     <mi>s</mi>
     <mi>y</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mspace width="0.28em"/>
    <msub>
     <mi>s</mi>
     <mi>x</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak">+</mo>
    <msub>
     <mi>s</mi>
     <mi>y</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>≤</mo>
    <mn>1</mn>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>.
</p>
